critique: This document is an executive order from 1939 regarding the assignment of radio frequencies to government radio stations. It outlines various regulations and definitions related to radio communication, including frequency usage, interference protocols, and station classifications. There is nothing about immigration, civil liberties, or social inclusion. It does not seem to expand executive power, but rather defines the rules for radio frequency use. It does not seem to favor state or federal primacy. It does not seem to promote economic regulation or deregulation. It does not seem to have an ideological tilt.
